<h1>@KJ{{exit}}@HI{{su}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @Vmasustem{{}}@KJ{{exit}}@HI{{su}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
@KJ{{exit}}@HI{{su}} is an auxiliary that indicates that something latent has been realised or something
has started to happen.
</p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{car}}ga@KJ{{move}}ki@KJ{{exit}}shimashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      The car started to move.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{rain}}ga@KJ{{descend}}ri@KJ{{exit}}shita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Suddenly it began to rain.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
The suffix @KJ{{exit}}@HI{{su}} usually indicates an abrupt and non-volitional start.
<a href="grammar-hajimeru-suffix.html">@HI{{hajimeru}}</a>, on the other hand, has a broader usage.
The antonym of both of these forms is a verb with the suffix <a href="grammar-owaru-suffix.html">@KJ{{end}}@HI{{waru}}</a>.
</p>

